hniques of recognition and cultural translation that emerge in response to these social uncertainties. In particular, Migrants in Translation focuses on Italian ethno-psychiatry as an emerging technique that provides culturally appropriate therapeutic services exclusively to migrants, political refugees, and victims of torture and trafficking. Cristiana Giordano argues that ethno-psychiatry’s focus on cultural identifications as therapeutic—inasmuch as it complies with current political desires for diversity and multiculturalism—also provides a radical critique of psychiatric, legal, and moral categories of inclusion, and allows for a rethinking of the politics of recognition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAssimilation (Sociology)xPsychological aspects. 0aCultural pluralism. 0aEthnopsychologyzItaly. 0aImmigrantsxCultural assimilationzItaly. 0aImmigrantsxMental healthzItaly. 0aMental health services. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  acontemporary italy.  acultural differences.  acultural identity.  acultural translation.  aeastern european immigrants.  aethno psychiatry.  aethnographers.  aethnography.  aeurope.  aeuropean identity.  aforeign migration.  aitaly.  amental health.  amigrant experience.  amodern history.  amulticultural society.  amulticulturalism.  amultiracial.  anational identity.  anorth african immigrants.  apolitical identity.  apolitical refugees.  areligious values.  asocial historians.  asub saharan african immigrants.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052027665940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095886940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520958869423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9